body: ``` clear all close all clc %put LEFT_elbowup.txt into matlab current matlab work folder A=importdata('/System/Volumes/Data/Users/Olive/Documents/GitHub/bc/dolphin/PythonDataHandlers/sample_emg_data/LEFT_elbowup.txt'); %A.data is a matrix with 7 , try ch 2 and 5 for example EMG1=A.data(:,2); EMG2=A.data(:,5); %Each EMG signal should have a 0 mean, but sometimes not, so %the easiest method for getting the data ready for processing is this: %make sure each signal has a mean of 0 before rectifying via abs EMG1=abs(EMG1-mean(EMG1)); EMG2=abs(EMG2-mean(EMG2)); %ok so now the two signals are ready for some basics %you need to make segments of your data, let's say 10s of data, split into %1s epochs, overlapped by 500ms, giving 20 segments. Fs = 1000; seglen=1000;%one second segments num_seconds=10; %want to use total of num_seconds of data for calculation overlap=.5;%half a segment startpoints= [0:overlap*Fs:num_seconds*Fs];%segment starting samples startpoints(1)=1; %create a matrix per signal where each row is a segment of the signal % this takes a span of data (in this case 10 seconds) and splits it into % segments. columns are time, rows are segments for i=1:length(startpoints)-1 EMG1mat(i,:)=EMG1(startpoints(i):startpoints(i)+seglen); EMG2mat(i,:)=EMG2(startpoints(i):startpoints(i)+seglen); %should make each signal have a mean of 0 again post rectification. a more %local removal of bias from 0-mean voltage EMG1mat(i,:)=EMG1mat(i,:)-mean(EMG1mat(i,:)); EMG2mat(i,:)=EMG2mat(i,:)-mean(EMG2mat(i,:)); end %signal 1 --> 20x1001 (20 segments, each row represents a moment in time at 1kHz.) %ok so now you can do a FFT on each row of each matrix %or you can do a DFT and just feed the coherence analysis directly %this will look like you have 20 complex numbers per frequency, per signal freqs = [5:50]; %make a time vector corresponding to 1s of samples timevec=[0:1/Fs:1]; %create a 'taper' or window that has a sum of 1 taper=hann(length(timevec))./sum(hann(length(timevec))); taper=taper';%to make it one row, for later vectorized multiplication tic % for each row (segment) do FFT on each row. result is rows: frequency, and % cols are segment #. dftmat1 and dftmat1 are a complex matrix. for f=1:length(freqs) for segment=1:size(EMG1mat,1)%20 rows = 20 segments % build a dft matrix, as described above; freqs x segments % multiply each segment by a complex sinusoid of a given freq. dftmat1(f,segment)=2*sum((exp(2*sqrt(-1)*pi*freqs(f).*timevec)).*EMG1mat(segment,:).*taper); dftmat2(f,segment)=2*sum((exp(2*sqrt(-1)*pi*freqs(f).*timevec)).*EMG2mat(segment,:).*taper); % start the coherence function by creating a cross spectrum matrix % elemtn by element, we're going to multiply signal 1's matrix by % signal2 matrix (after we get the complex conjugate of it). %TODO move outside the loop so we can do it as matrix multiplication. % coh-setup-mat is the 'cross spectrum', for each segment as a big % complex matrix. coh_setup_mat(f,segment)=dftmat1(f,segment)*conj(dftmat2(f,segment)); end end %for every frequency (row) you now have a N complex numbers (columns) %where each is a new segment of data %now do coherence % for each row (frequency) for f=1:length(freqs) % todo change to colsums sum_of_cross_spectrum_for_given_freq = sum(coh_setup_mat(f,:)); coh_numerator = abs(sum_of_cross_spectrum_for_given_freq)^2; % taking the magnitude of the complex values gives you the amplitudes % (the power spectra). when you square them it makes it into 'power' % add up all the power (that's ththis whole part). % if perfect alignment in phase, numerator will be exactly equal to % the denominator. coh_denomenator=sum(abs(dftmat1(f,:)).^2) * sum(abs(dftmat2(f,:)).^2); coh(f)=coh_numerator/coh_denomenator; end %coh is a 1x46 because we have 46 frequencies. these are 0 to 1 values. time_for_dft_method=toc %now make the mscohere function operate just as above %in this case just stick all the segments together into a vector EMG1new=[];EMG2new=[]; for i=1:size(EMG1mat,1) EMG1new=[EMG1new,EMG1mat(i,:)]; EMG2new=[EMG2new,EMG2mat(i,:)]; end tic % mscohere expects: EMG1new % 0 is the overlap is 0. but the input is already overlapped. [coh2 f2]=mscohere(EMG1new,EMG2new,hann(1001),0,freqs,Fs); time_for_mscohere=toc figure() plot(freqs,coh,'k','linewidth',2) hold on plot(freqs,coh2,'--r','linewidth',2) legend('new','mscohere') title('it works') %compare with entire signal rather than just the first 10 seconds or so. %using more segments will push this plot to look identical to the previous. figure() [coh3 f3]=mscohere(zscore(EMG1),zscore(EMG2),hann(1000),500,freqs,Fs); plot(freqs,coh3) title('entire signal') ```

title: design primary results
body:
# 1. What is the dimensionality of control in the mapping of tendon driven force production of a real human hand, both forwards and backwards? 
**If we answer this**, we could 
a. understand & build better prosthetics
b. better choose tendon transfer insertion points
c. decide how muscle prosthetics (i.e. CDMRP) would affect transduction of force and outward control.

# 2. How does the learning algorithm reduce dimensionality and leverage the null space? 
**if we could answer this**
a. insight on how our nervous system must deal with the multidimensional problem of control.

# 3. How can complexity of the forward (hi to low) and inverse (lo to high) mappings help us understand the underlying mechanisms that can be used in their control? If you simplify the system does it make a linear mapping as accurate as a nonlinear mapping? 
**If we know the answer to this** 
a. develop a deeper understanding of how mappings that change dimensionality can be harnessed by nonlinear interactions or linear interactions in a dimensionality-dependent paradigm. 
b. Answer for: When does nonlinearity become important? 
c. We observe that nervous system circuits have different levels of complexity—can we explain for the complexity disparities across CNS by examining the need for nonlinearity in the model composure for each of the forward and inverse mappings.

===============================
# Result Figures (matching prior numbers)
## 1. forward mapping with LRM and NN perform best
- this is the first time we are studying tenodn driven limb forward and backward. the mapping is fully characterized. if you have the mapping, you can produce new prosthetics and understand how control will be affect by changes in the plant.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13772726/45457495-0172e980-b6a4-11e8-9e11-0c83bcb45471.png)

> **Figure Carbon: Forward costs shows a nonlinear model does not outperform linear model** Across all cost functions, no significant difference between the NN and the LRM in predicting output forces, given the input of the input muscle activations.



## 2.  non-normality of NN output distributions (inverse)
- maybe this is the way animals deal with an overdetermined problem
![pasted_image_9_12_18__3_55_pm](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13772726/45457559-675f7100-b6a4-11e8-9896-7d13a2fdd4e6.jpg)

> **Figure Nitrogen: Nonlinear mapping generates bimodal distributions of solutions, while linear mappings create unimodal distributions**. For the test set, for any given solution, the mapping must choose one solution (of the many that would work) to put forward as its prediction. The NN preferentially chooses multiple parts of the subspace, while linear mapping chooses the center. Both avoid the extremes.

## 3. inverse performance of NN surpassing LRM
- different parts of the nervous system need different levels of complexity. cerebellum is more intertwined so it can deal with more complexity, while forward might work with simple spinal reflexes. reticulospinal tract might be a bit more simplistic for forward control. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13772726/45457626-bdccaf80-b6a4-11e8-93d1-f6eaa330398a.png)
> **Figure Oxygen: Inverse mapping performance was always better with a nonlinear mapping.** While the LRM and NN were comparable for forward modeling (as in Figure Carbon, where dimensionality was brought from 7 dimensions to 6), the inverse model (with 6 to 7 dimensions) appears to benefit from 

Discussion points:
did our network create a specific node that's responsible for a horizontal Fx?



Intro Figures:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13772726/45456867-3893cb80-b6a1-11e8-96f3-093eeffca125.png)

> **Figure Boron:** Inverse cost interpretations must acknowledge muscle redundancy.



Methods:
===============================================
===============================================
===============================================


![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13772726/45456844-244fce80-b6a1-11e8-8d1e-55332eee456c.png)

> **Figure Hydrogen: Forward Map** This schematic explains how the different algorithms are posed with learning the relationship between input activations the the resultant output wrench. For clarity, we illustrate forces in 2 dimensions; however, cost functions for all figures are evaluated on the entire six-dimensional wrench. All statistics and numbers are ficticious with inspiration from data observed and used for reader comprehension of the concepts.


===============================================
===============================================
===============================================

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13772726/45456850-2a45af80-b6a1-11e8-8bd3-82f5671b8983.png)

> **Figure Helium: Inverse Map** This schematic explains how the different algorithms are posed with learning the inverse relationship of tension transduction to wrench—the learning models each learn how to predict activations, given an input of a wrench. As in Figure Hydrogen, we illustrate forces in 2 dimensions but evaluate on 6-dimensions in the results, and numbers are fictitious for the schematic.
===============================================
===============================================
===============================================
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13772726/45456857-2fa2fa00-b6a1-11e8-8785-973f4e89254e.png)

> **Figure Lithium** Evaluating the error between observed activations and predicted activations by the inverse model is incomplete. The loop model paradigm is used to produce highly interpretable costs for different inverse models, by accomodating for muscle redundancy.


===============================================
===============================================
===============================================
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13772726/45456863-33cf1780-b6a1-11e8-9f36-61869449cb96.png)

> **Figure Berillium:** Overview of the Forward, Inverse, and Loop prediction paradigms used to evaluate mapping performance.
